i## What's Gopher		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iGopher is a protocol born in the early ages of the Internet. It was		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iinvented at the University of Minnesota in 1991, with a purpose		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isimilar to HTTP today. The protocol itself is extremely simple:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Client connects to TCP port 70 of the server, and send one line of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   URL ending with CRLF, e.g. `some_dir/hello.txt`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. Server sends data of the requested file and closes the connection.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. And we're done.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe server could be returning a text file, a picture, a binary file,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ior a Gopher list file called `Gophermap` with special formatting. Each		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iline of the file is composed of the following fields:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. A character representing the type of this line, may it be text ( `i` ),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   a link to a text file ( `0` ), a link to another Gophermap ( `1` ),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   a picture ( `I` ), or a binary ( `9` ). Of course, there are other		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   types meant for protocols no longer used today. See		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
h   RFC1436 Section 3.8	URL:https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1436#section-3.8	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   for more details.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. A message line to be shown for this line, e.g., `Hello World` .		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. A TAB character.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i4. Target path of the link, e.g., `/some_dir/hello.txt` .		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i5. A TAB character.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i6. Target hostname of the link, e.g., `gopher.lantian.pub` .		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i7. A TAB character.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i8. Target port of the link, usually `70` .		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i9. CR+LF as line ending.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAt the end of the `Gophermap` there is a single period on its own		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iline, marking the end of the map.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTake a look at these examples:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # A line of information. It has no link target for part 4, and you may fill anything for the target host and port		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  iHello World[TAB][TAB]invalid.host[TAB]70[CR][LF]		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Example of a link		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  iProject Description[TAB]/project/description.txt[TAB]gopher.lantian.pub[TAB]70[CR][LF]		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Example of a picture		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  iScreenshot[TAB]/project/screenshot.jpg[TAB]gopher.lantian.pub[TAB]70[CR][LF]		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # End marker of Gophermap		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  .[CR][LF]		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iUnder the background of lacking computing power, the Gopher protocol		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwas widely used in the 1990s due to its extreme simplicity. But since		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe only thing a client can do is to send a URL, it is much more		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icomplicated to allow the client to post data onto the server, like for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isearching or comment sections. In addition, the server can only return		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe file itself but nothing else, unlike HTTP where additional		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iresponse headers are allowed. This means the client needs to find out		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe type of response based on previous Gophermaps, or even guess on		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iits own. Therefore, Gopher was eventually replaced with functionally		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isuperior HTTP.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut Gopher protocol isn't dead. As of now (the year 2021), there are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istill actively maintained Gopher server software such as		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hGophernicus	URL:https://github.com/gophernicus/gophernicus	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i, and there are sites serving over Gopher.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
