i## Let Nginx support Gopher		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNginx, by itself, is an HTTP server. Let us ignore for a moment the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imodern HTTP/2.0 with binary commands, or UDP-based QUIC or HTTP/3.0,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand look back at the HTTP/1.1, which was once widely used. Back then,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ia request looks like this:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  GET /test.php HTTP/1.1		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Host: localhost		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  User-Agent: curl/7.75.0		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Accept: */*		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  HTTP/1.1 200 OK		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Server: nginx/1.18.0		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Date: Sun, 21 Mar 2021 12:08:07 GMT		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Transfer-Encoding: chunked		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Connection: keep-alive		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  X-Powered-By: PHP/8.0.3		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe first part is the client request, of which `GET http://localhost/		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHTTP/1.1` and `Host: localhost` are necessary. They tell the server		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe path ( `/test.php` ) and domain ( `localhost` ) the client is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itrying to access.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe other parts, such as User-Agent headers commonly seen, are not an		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iessential part of the HTTP protocol. We can connect to the server		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imanually with `telnet localhost 80` and only send the first two lines:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  GET /test.php HTTP/1.1		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Host: localhost		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  HTTP/1.1 200 OK		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Server: nginx/1.18.0		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Date: Sun, 21 Mar 2021 12:13:58 GMT		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Transfer-Encoding: chunked		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Connection: keep-alive		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  X-Powered-By: PHP/8.0.3		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  c		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Hello World		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  0		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ^CConnection closed by foreign host.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe server still gave back contents for the page, but there are things		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imore than we actually need:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Gopher clients won't recognize the 200 status code of HTTP;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- There are extra response headers including Date, Content-Type, etc.;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- The responses of Nginx are encoded with `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` ,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  which Gopher clients have no idea about;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- We need to press Enter twice after the `Host:` line before Nginx		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  sends the response. Gopher clients will only do it once;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Most importantly, have you noticed the `^C` ? It's there because I		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  manually pressed `Ctrl+C` to terminate the connection. Nginx has `Connection:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  keep-alive` enabled by default and won't actively close the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  connection after the request is completed. Instead, it will wait for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  the client to send a second request. A Gopher client, in this case,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  will wait forever.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTherefore, there's too much to change based on HTTP/1.1. But if		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithere's 1.1, there's also 1.0. How about we have a try of HTTP/1.0?		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  GET /test.php HTTP/1.0		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  HTTP/1.1 200 OK		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Server: nginx/1.18.0		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Date: Sun, 21 Mar 2021 12:20:24 GMT		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Connection: close		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  X-Powered-By: PHP/8.0.3		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Hello World		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThis time, the server actively closed the connection, and returned raw		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idata instead of `chunk` encoded ones, which is good. But there are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istill extra HTTP response headers. Do we need to disable all logic		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irelated to HTTP headers? There's still a lot to do. And we still need		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito press Enter twice, by the way.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHere's some good news: there was an extremely simple version of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHTTP/0.9 before HTTP/1.0, and it is just a single line:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  GET /test.php		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Hello World		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe client only sent the first `GET` line. Once it sends a line feed,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNginx replies back `Hello World` without needing the second line feed,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwithout status code 200 or other headers, and not forgetting to close		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe connection. This is very close to what we want: the HTTP client		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isent `GET /test.php[ENTER]` this time, while a Gopher client will		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprobably send `test.php[ENTER]` .		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNow we have a plan: add a protocol to parse Gopher requests, set the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irequest type to GET, add a slash `/` before the URL, and copy/reuse		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHTTP/0.9 logic for the rest part.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
